        content: '<div class="bloc1"><ul><li>Stablecoins provide a degree of stability in a volatile ecosystem - they’re the closest you can get to holding fiat on-chain.</li></ul><ul><li>Stablecoins provide a degree of stability in a volatile ecosystem - they’re the closest you can get to holding fiat on-chain.</li></ul><li>There are several types of stablecoin technology, each with different properties.</li></ul><ul><li>Stablecoins provide a degree of stability in a volatile ecosystem - they’re the closest you can get to holding fiat on-chain.</li></ul><li>There are several types of stablecoin technology, each with different properties.</li></ul><li>You can generate more interest on stablecoins than holding fiat in the bank — but where there’s reward there’s risk!</li></ul><p>Stablecoins are a category of token used by both new and experienced Explorers — they’re an integral part of the DeFi ecosystem. So why are so many power users holding them?</p><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><li> Holding stablecoins is very much like holding fiat currency in a self-custody wallet. When holding Circle’s US dollar stablecoin (USDC) for example, you can expect these holdings to maintain 1:1 value with the US dollar while the prices of assets like Ether and Bitcoin fluctuate around you. </li></ul><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><li> Holding stablecoins is very much like holding fiat currency in a self-custody wallet. When holding Circle’s US dollar stablecoin (USDC) for example, you can expect these holdings to maintain 1:1 value with the US dollar while the prices of assets like Ether and Bitcoin fluctuate around you. </li></ul><li><strong>Flexibility:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><li> Holding stablecoins is very much like holding fiat currency in a self-custody wallet. When holding Circle’s US dollar stablecoin (USDC) for example, you can expect these holdings to maintain 1:1 value with the US dollar while the prices of assets like Ether and Bitcoin fluctuate around you. </li></ul><li><strong>Flexibility:</strong></li></ul><li> Because this pegged value is in the form of an ERC-20 token on the blockchain, we’re always only ever one DEX transaction away from moving our fiat value to crypto value, or vice-versa.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><li> Holding stablecoins is very much like holding fiat currency in a self-custody wallet. When holding Circle’s US dollar stablecoin (USDC) for example, you can expect these holdings to maintain 1:1 value with the US dollar while the prices of assets like Ether and Bitcoin fluctuate around you. </li></ul><li><strong>Flexibility:</strong></li></ul><li> Because this pegged value is in the form of an ERC-20 token on the blockchain, we’re always only ever one DEX transaction away from moving our fiat value to crypto value, or vice-versa.</li></ul><li><strong>Access:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Stability:</strong></li></ul><li> Holding stablecoins is very much like holding fiat currency in a self-custody wallet. When holding Circle’s US dollar stablecoin (USDC) for example, you can expect these holdings to maintain 1:1 value with the US dollar while the prices of assets like Ether and Bitcoin fluctuate around you. </li></ul><li><strong>Flexibility:</strong></li></ul><li> Because this pegged value is in the form of an ERC-20 token on the blockchain, we’re always only ever one DEX transaction away from moving our fiat value to crypto value, or vice-versa.</li></ul><li><strong>Access:</strong></li></ul><li> By holding stablecoins, we’re also unlocking a range of decentralized financial services, like permissionless lending & borrowing, where we can lend our fiat-pegged tokens to internet citizens in exchange for regular interest payments!</li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><li><strong>Crypto-collateralized:</strong></li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><li><strong>Crypto-collateralized:</strong></li></ul><li> overcollateralized by crypto deposits into DeFi protocols.</li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><li><strong>Crypto-collateralized:</strong></li></ul><li> overcollateralized by crypto deposits into DeFi protocols.</li></ul><li>🔃 </li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><li><strong>Crypto-collateralized:</strong></li></ul><li> overcollateralized by crypto deposits into DeFi protocols.</li></ul><li>🔃 </li></ul><li><strong>Algorithmic:</strong></li></ul><ul><li>💵 </li></ul><li><strong>Fiat-backed: </strong></li></ul><li>1:1 collateralized through fiat deposits in real-world institutions.</li></ul><li>🪙 </li></ul><li><strong>Crypto-collateralized:</strong></li></ul><li> overcollateralized by crypto deposits into DeFi protocols.</li></ul><li>🔃 </li></ul><li><strong>Algorithmic:</strong></li></ul><li> fixed to supply/demand algorithms that maintain price stability.</li></ul><p>The high degree of centralization in the fiat-backed stablecoin sector leaves a lot to be desired for holding fiat-pegged value on the blockchain.</p><p>Crypto-collateralized stablecoins are transparent and fairly decentralized, eliminating certain off and on-chain risks. Maintain their fiat peg by crypto asset backing. They endure crypto market volatility by overcollateralization. All assets are controlled by Ethereum accounts. Notable example is MakerDAO’s DAI.</p><p>Considerations:</p><ul><li><strong>Censorship Risk:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Censorship Risk:</strong></li></ul><li> Because both USDC and BUSD are beholden to government regulation, their token smart contracts include a freeze function whereby a customer’s on-chain holdings can be locked in cases of disagreeable activity — even when held in a non-custodial wallet. </li></ul><ul><li><strong>Collateral Valuation:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Collateral Valuation:</strong></li></ul><li> The stablecoin’s reserves typically consist of both other stablecoins and crypto. For example, DAI is backed by USDC, BTC, ETH and a number of other tokens. To mitigate the risks of this diverse range of assets, DAI is overcollateralized by 25% at the moment.\nSource: </li></ul><ul><li><strong>Collateral Valuation:</strong></li></ul><li> The stablecoin’s reserves typically consist of both other stablecoins and crypto. For example, DAI is backed by USDC, BTC, ETH and a number of other tokens. To mitigate the risks of this diverse range of assets, DAI is overcollateralized by 25% at the moment.\nSource: </li></ul><li>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1316928/dai-reserves-breakdown/</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Collateral Valuation:</strong></li></ul><li> The stablecoin’s reserves typically consist of both other stablecoins and crypto. For example, DAI is backed by USDC, BTC, ETH and a number of other tokens. To mitigate the risks of this diverse range of assets, DAI is overcollateralized by 25% at the moment.\nSource: </li></ul><li>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1316928/dai-reserves-breakdown/</li></ul><li><strong>Counterparty Risk:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Collateral Valuation:</strong></li></ul><li> The stablecoin’s reserves typically consist of both other stablecoins and crypto. For example, DAI is backed by USDC, BTC, ETH and a number of other tokens. To mitigate the risks of this diverse range of assets, DAI is overcollateralized by 25% at the moment.\nSource: </li></ul><li>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1316928/dai-reserves-breakdown/</li></ul><li><strong>Counterparty Risk:</strong></li></ul><li> Because crypto-collateralized stablecoins rely on a reserve of diverse holdings, there’s a higher chance of your value being affected — though it could be argued that you’re also mitigating the impact of these risks.</li></ul><p>We can take a look at the leading stablecoins by market cap to get an idea of what the market prefers. While this shouldn’t indicate how you should position yourself, it does give an overview of the stablecoin climate.\nAt the time of writing, the top ten stablecoins (by market cap) have a total allocation of approximately $128 billion USD in value, with $122 billion allocated to fiat-backed, $4.7 billion to crypto-collateralized, and $1.3 billion to algorithmic stablecoins.\n<em>(Source: </em><em>https://defillama.com/stablecoins</em><em>)</em></p><p>While most centralized exchanges offer popular fiat-backed stablecoins (and typically their own branded stablecoin), it can be difficult to find crypto-collateralized and algorithmic stablecoins on centralized exchanges. You’ll likely have to visit a decentralized exchange to pick up these tokens, so check out the ‘Decentralized Exchange’ lesson if you haven’t yet!</p><p>Did you know that you can lend out your stablecoin balance and generate interest? There’s a whole ecosystem of trustless DeFi loans that connects lenders and borrowers, with on-chain collateral and smart contracts managing risk under the hood. You’re looking at annual returns far higher than available to you in the traditional banking sector — around the 2%-5% mark — but of course where there’s reward, there’s risk!</p><p>The Lending & Borrowing topic deserves its own Bankless Academy entry, but if you’re keen to learn more you can check out platforms like Aave.com and Curve.fi.</p><ul><li><strong>Dynamic Holdings:</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Dynamic Holdings:</strong></li></ul><li> Your number of token holdings will fluctuate slightly with the token supply, but the total value of the tokens will remain constant.</li></ul><p></p><p>The smart contract address for any given token can change based on the network you are using. While many large DEXs have a token whitelist, you may need to find the correct token listing and verify the smart contract address with the token issuer before you purchase a token on a DEX.\nScammers have been known to take advantage of this user experience hiccup by deploying fake tokens and luring DeFi users to trade into them. Always double check the smart contract address with the issuer — legitimate projects have this information on their website.</p></div><div class="bloc2"><img src="https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/c8c73987-3c95-40b6-93c8-a9f347b230c6/Instructor_-_Medium.png?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD&X-Amz-Credential=AKIAT73L2G45EIPT3X45%2F20230703%2Fus-west-2%2Fs3%2Faws4_request&X-Amz-Date=20230703T180818Z&X-Amz-Expires=3600&X-Amz-Signature=073162f47a6e16f61f49654f61ad33a7afbff139b6398737a9d6737744a94fdd&X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host&x-id=GetObject"></div>'
